  "findings": [
    {
      "kind": "exact_transfer_divergence",
      "summary": "PAEBrightness per-pixel transfer: TS (per-channel sRGB multiply) matches FCP EXACTLY on GRAY inputs (<=0.2 level, quantisation) at all amounts, but DIVERGES HARD on SATURATED-COLOUR inputs. E.g. in=(50,200,50) amt=1.5: FCP=[179,255,161] vs TS=[75,255,75] (104-level error on R).",
      "diagnosis": "FCP's Brightness is NOT a per-channel multiply. On gray it's indistinguishable from one, but on a saturated colour the LOW channels are boosted far more than x1.5 (R 50->179 = x3.58). Neither plain sRGB multiply (->75) nor plain linear-light multiply (->62) reproduces 179 \u2014 so the working space is something else (candidates: a luminance/luma-preserving scale, a Rec709/gamma working space with cross-channel coupling, or an HDR tone curve). This is the concrete RE lead the coupled delta-response (ddb=6.0) could not localise.",
      "why_this_matters": "The TRANSFER-FUNCTION node kind isolates a pointwise colour node EXACTLY (uniform-colour inputs are conform-invariant), sidestepping the pipeline coupling AND the headless-vs-GUI colour-management gap that made colour nodes read as unattributable 5-13 dB DIVERGED. It converts 'colour subsystem is a blind spot' into a precise per-input divergence table.",
      "next": "Decode PAEBrightness's real per-pixel math from the binary (levels.ts cites HGColorMatrix / a working-space multiply). Sweep more inputs (full sat/hue grid) to fit the exact transfer, then correct brightnessFilter. VERIFY here (tol 2 levels) and cross-check the GUI gate (fct score) net-positive before shipping (oracle_truth caveat still applies to the ABSOLUTE level, but the COLOUR-COUPLING divergence is real regardless of gamma)."
    }
  ]
